Text.SourceString: I was telling the mayor I didn’t think anyone would want to visit the island until we got rid of the oil at the beach, but you proved me wrong.//Welcome to the community!
Yeah, you’re right. The island isn’t like it used to be.//It is what it is.
I like to spend my Spring mornings in Garden Lane.//<portrait=happy>It’s close by, and have you seen the area? Incredibly gorgeous.
The museum is nice and warm now.//Not too hot, not too cold. It’s comfortable to work there in Spring.
My brooch? Er…//<portrait=normal>It’s special to me. Not expensive. Nothing like that.//<NPCName>Sunny</> gave it to me the day we brought <NPCName>Oliver</> home from Pokyo.
The heat can get intense at the beach this time of year.//<portrait=concerned>Even with the windows open, sometimes it’s still hot, even at night.
<NPCName>Suki</> has great bug repellent. I believe she makes it herself.//It comes in handy in Summer.
Oof! No more humidity. I have to manually curl my hair now.//<portrait=normal>Good thing I have short hair.
Oof! No more humidity. I have to manually curl my hair now.//<portrait=normal>Good thing I have short hair.

The Beach Shack has been smoking a lot of salmon lately.//<portrait=annoyed>The smoke gets trapped on the second floor all day… No matter how many times we change our clothes, we end up smelling like smoked salmon.
I’ve been telling those two that’s what happens, but nope. They still insist. All right, then. What can I say?//<NPCName>Jim</> and <NPCName>Sunny</> are in charge of the kitchen.
When a caterpillar spins its chrysalis, it’s an ugly little thing! But then a beautiful butterfly emerges.//And lychees are the same… Ugly on the outside, but soft and sweet on the inside.
Well… I don’t know if that’s a very good analogy, to be honest.//I just know I love those little fruits!
I’m glad we have a good coffee bar here in Starlet Town, but to tell you the truth, I much prefer green tea.//<portrait=happy>Don’t tell <NPCName>Raj</>!
Green tea has a lot of health benefits. It may even protect the brain from aging! But mainly, I like the taste.
We’re always looking for donations for the museum. Please stop by if you have any interesting bugs you’d like to share!
Catch any good bugs lately? Bring them to the museum if you want to contribute to our insect exhibit.
This rain isn’t good for our caterpillars! I covered the terrarium with a plastic bin.//We don’t want those little guys to drown!
Oh, gosh… It’s storming, all right.
This rain isn’t good for our caterpillars! I covered the terrarium with a plastic bin. We don’t want those little guys to drown!//I’m going to go and cover more of them.
It’s raining pretty hard. I should be going home.
It’s raining pretty hard. I should be going home.
This rain isn’t good for our caterpillars! I covered the terrarium with a plastic bin. We don’t want those little guys to drown!//I’m going to go and cover more of them.
The museum is cold in Winter.//I guess the high ceiling doesn’t help. It gets <Italic>really</> cold at times.
Sometimes at night, I take <NPCName>Oliver</> to the porch on the second floor, and we watch the snow falling on the water.
I love watching butterflies fly from flower to flower. They’re so graceful and elegant.
<NPCName>Oliver’s</> given me an opportunity I didn’t think I’d ever have—being a mom.//If it weren’t for his biological mother’s bravery, my story would’ve been so much different.
Days like these make you think, don’t they?//It certainly takes me back to when we first brought <NPCName>Oliver</> home.

I didn’t bond with him right away. I was worried, of course.//Maybe I wasn’t cut out to be—to be his mom. You know, those thoughts.//<portrait=annoyed>I didn’t fall in love right away, and I had so much shame back then…//<portrait=normal>All in the past now. Can’t think of my life without my son.
Days like these make you think, don’t they?//It certainly takes me back to when we first brought <NPCName>Oliver</> home.

I didn’t bond with him right away. I was worried, of course.//Maybe I wasn’t cut out to be—to be his mom. You know, those thoughts.//<portrait=annoyed>I didn’t fall in love right away, and I had so much shame back then…//<portrait=normal>All in the past now. Can’t think of my life without my son.
At first, right after we brought <NPCName>Oliver</> home, I thought I wasn’t mom material.//Doubts… They get to you sometimes.
But in time, it just felt like everything fell into place. I don’t know how or when it started. The next thing I knew, he called me Mom… And that’s who I’ve been from then on.
I always knew deep down that being a mom was something I was meant to do, and adopting <NPCName>Oliver</> just confirmed it.//Even when it didn’t go as well as I thought it would at first…

I’d been waiting to be a mom for far too long.//<portrait=concerned>And <NPCName>Sunny</>—of course, he was made to be a dad. You can just tell these things right away.//I knew it the moment he met my nieces.
Some kids came to the museum the other day, and gosh oh gosh…<NPCName>Scott</> loves kids, and kids adore him!//<portrait=normal>He reminds me a lot of <NPCName>Sunny</>.
It’s interesting how flies can sense when something is rotting or decaying. It’s like they have a sixth sense or something.//Morbid, I know.
I feel bad for flies. Everyone seems to hate them, but they’re just trying to do their part in the world.
I mean, sure, flies can be a nuisance when they’re around your food, but they’re just looking for a meal like any other living thing.

You might think Summer is when there are the most flies, but that’s actually not true.//<portrait=normal>Yeah, maybe in some parts of the world, but here in Starlet Town, the flies are out year round.
Summertime here is lively!//<portrait=happy>The beach, the shack. People are vivacious.
I can’t believe it’s already Summer. Time flies, huh?
I’m thinking of replanting my garden outside the bedroom.//Do you have any good tips for gardening?
If I plant flowers this Spring, what do you think I should plant? Peonies or daisies?
The salty air makes it hard for plants to grow in front of the shack. Often, a lot of them die, and the only things left are the bushes.
The only thing I need in this sleepy weather is a cup of green tea.
I can’t believe it’s already Fall. Where did Summer go?
I’m surprised often, aren’t I?//Well, what can I say? The change of season always surprises me. A good kind of surprise!

I’m thinking of having a bonfire tomorrow evening with <NPCName>Oliver</> and maybe some of his friends.//It would be in front of the inn, not by the shack. There’s just more room for the kids to play.
We may not do it, though. <NPCName>Oliver</> doesn’t like going out at night.
I can’t wait for the Winter Fair.//The beach is lively again. The best part is we can see the pretty lights from the shack.

We’ve been making ramen at the shack lately.//<portrait=normal>Maybe I’ll roast some chestnuts tonight. It’s <NPCName>Sunny’s</> favorite.//<portrait=happy>We still have some chestnuts from Fall… I hope.

It’s nice to see kids enjoying the snow and building snowmen.//<portrait=normal>Some of the kids I watched building snowmen a long time ago are grown up now. The twins who run the inn,<NpcName>Frankie Jr.</>…//<portrait=happy>Gosh! I’m old!
<NPCName>Sunny</> can be loud sometimes. But that’s just his personality.//<portrait=normal>Yeah, and his voice…
